sh at New\nOrleans by General Jackson War\nof the U. S. with the Dey of Al\ngiers. 16 Indiana admitted to the Union\nCharter granted to the Second\nBank of the U. S. flection of\nJames Monroe President of the\nU. S.\n17 Inauguration of James Monroe,\nAdmission of Mississippi to the\nAmerican Union.\nWinn In\n1 I M\nG. E BAKER\n1808 One Hundred Years\nt\nV\nx\nThe history of this store goes\nback a full century, to the time\nwhen Stafford was but a small\nhamlet and long before the steam\nrailroad invaded its borders. At\nthat time this was the main ar\ntery for the stage line between\nNew York and Boston, then a\nthree-days' trip which is made\nover our modern steam railroads\nin five hours. Many are the\nevents of interest that have tran\nspired since 1808. We chronicle\na few of them.\nThe growth of our business has\nkept pace with the times Our\noriginal quarters were a ;small\nstory and half building. We now\noccupy, a large three-story brick\nblock sin the center of the Bor\nough, with a floor space of over\nsixteen thousand (16,000) square\nfeet. Our stock of Furniture and\nHouse Furnishing goods is larger\nand more complete than that\nshown by any house in this\ncounty.\n100 Years in Business Means Something\nFURNITURE AND\nl-I\"I\"I\"M\"M\"l-I\"I\"I\"I\"l\"I\":\"I\"I\"I\"I\"I\"l\"IvIM\"\n1878-1882\n1878 The remonetization of sil\nverYellow fever In the South\nThe \"Molly Maguire\" outrages\nGeneraKjrant makes a tour around\nthe world.\n7iV End of financial panic of 1873\nand resumption of specie payment.\n80 National census the popula\ntion of the U. S. 50,150783 -Treaty\nmade with China The Greely ex\npedition to North Pole President\nGarfield elected 763 labor strikes\noccurred in the U. S. during the\nyear.\n'8 1 Assassination of President Gar\nfield by Guiteau. July 2 Chester\nA. Arthur sworn in as President\nStar route frauds Celebration of\nYork town centennial.\n'8Ji Charles Guiteau executed Re\nlief for thetireely expedition starts\nout Lieutenant Lqckwood and\nSergeant Brainard reach the most\nnortherly point attained by an\nAmerican.\n1818-1822\n1818 General Jackson's invasion of\nFlorida Publication of living's\n\"Sketch Book\" First pensions\ngranted by Congress.\n19 Admission of Alabama to the\nAmerican Union First voyage\nacross the Atlantic by a vessel (the\n\"Savannah\") using steam Birth\nof James Russell Lowell (d. 1891).\n20 -Adoption in the U. S. of the\nMissouri Compromise, excluding\nSlavery from the territories north\nof latitude 30 deg. 30 min. Ad\nmission of Maine to the Union\nRe-election of James Monroe\nBirth of General Sherman (d. 1891).\n21 Mexico establishes independ\nenceCession of Florida to the U\nS. by Spain Admission of Mis\nsouri to the Union Publication of\nCooper's \"The Spy\" Birth of\nJenny Lind (d. 1887)\n'22 Birth of General Grant (d. 1885)\nH l -M-f-H-H-\ns i M\nj!\nStafford Springs,\n1883-1887\n1 883 Brooklyn bridge is now open\ned Exploration of Alaska Greely\nexpedition homeward bound.\n'84 Grover Cleveland elected Presi\ndent of the U. S. Official presenta\ntion of the Bartholdi Statue Gen\neral Sherman retires from com\nmand of the Army.\n'85 Death of General Grant Sur\nrender of the Apaches Iarge la\nbor strikes all over the country.\n80 Death of General Hancock\nThe Charleston earthquake oc\ncurred Anarchistic riot in Chicago\nGeneral Miles captures Geronimo\nNiagara Falls Power Company\nincorporated.\n37 Trouble in Hawaii The Read\ninar Railway strike Trouble be\ntween England and Venezuela..\n1823-1827\n1823 Enunciation\nthe Monroe\nDoctrine in the\nannual message of\nthe President of th\nU. S.\n'24 -PresidentiaLelecion in the U. S.\ne by the pop\nular vote the elettion of John\nQuincy Adams was\nmade by the\nHouse of Represmtatives Visit\nof Lafayette to the (J. S. Birth of\nStonewall Jackson Ai. 1863) Birth\nof George W. Curttf(d. 1892).\n25 Homoeopathy i itroduced into\nthe U. S. Lafayet e lays corner\nstone of Bunker H 11 Monument\nOpening of the Erie Canal from\nLake Erie to the Hudson River.\n'26 Abduction of V illiam Morgan\nand anti Masonic! excitement in\nNew York.\nt\n'27 Extinction of slavery in the\nState of New York4 South Carolina\nRailroad chartered! First railroad\nbuilt in U. S. using steam.\nv\nOUR ORIGINAL LOCATION.\nBuilding as enlarged from a story and half to\nabove size in 1868.\nj ir-i\n7 \"iliHRTOs\nv u\n.OUR PRESENT QUARTERS.\nEVERYTHING IN THE LINE OF\nHOUSE FURNISHING\n1888-1892\n1 888 Death of General Sheridan\nPresident Harrison elected -Knights\nof Labor strike ,on the\nSouthwestern Railroad system.\n'8V Hurricane destroyed the Ameri-.\ncan warships in harbor at Samoa\nBursting of the Johnstown dam\nSecretary of Agriculture added to\nthe Cabinet.\nThe \"Messiah Craze\" among\nthe Indians Death of Sitting\nBull Chicago chosen for the\nWord's Fair-Th'e McKinley tariff\nbill passed.\n'91 Threatened war with Chili\nDeath of General Sherman Treaty\nrights of Hawaii Death of King\nKalak.au of Hawaii Lieutenant\nfcary's Arctic expedition sails.\n'92 President Cleveland elected for\nthe second time Labor strikes at\nHomestead, P. Grounds of the\nWorld's Fair opened at Chicago\nFour hqndreth anniversary of the\ndiscovery of America.\n1828-1832\n1828 Election of General Andrew\nJackson President of the U. S.\nBeginning- of the construction of\nthe Baltimore Ohio Railroad.\n'29 Inauguration of President Jack-\nson Introduction of the \"spoils\nsystem\" in American national poli\ntics Abolition of slavery in MexicoLucifer-\nmatches manufac\ntured.\n30 Debate between Webster and\nHayne in the U. S. Senate -Steel\npens manufactured.\n'31 Nat. Turner's slave rising in Vir\nginiaBirth of General Sheridan\nMcCormick invents the reaping\nmachine Discovery of magneto\nelectricity by Faraday.\n'32 -Cholera in the U. S. Proclama\ntion of President Jackson against\nthe nullification movement Re\nelection of President Jackson\nThe Indian war in America called\nthe Black Hawk War.\nCO.\nOld To-Day 1908\n\"1\nHerjry 0. Baker, with his broth-.\ner, John, was' the founder of this\nbusiness, which he carried on un\ntil his death in 1851, when he was\nsucceeded by his son, Gilbert H.\nBaker, who successfully conduct\ned the business up to the time of\nhis death in. 1887. Since then the\n'business has been, and still is,\nrun under the same firm name\nG. H. Baker Co. F. H. Baker,\nmanager. The first location of\nthe business was on East Main\nstreei, about one-half mile from\nour present quarters. The orig\ninal building, with some addi\ntions,1 fs now standing on the old\nsite. The busiuess was carried\non in these quarters until 1878,\nwhen it was -removed to the pres-\nent lppation.\nWe know of no other business\nwhicn has been carried on for so\nlong, a time by persons in direct\nline of male descent from the\nfounder of the house.\nI\nConn.\n1893-1897\n1893 Statue -erected to Nathan\nHale Labor strikes afl over the\ncountry.\n'94: Sources of the Mississippi River\ndiscovered March of \"The Com\nmonweal Army\" The Chicago\nriots.\n'95 The Altanta exposition opened\nThe Brooklyn trolley strike\nWater power of Niagara Falls put\nto use Cuban revolt.\n9J General McKinley elected\nPresident of the U. S. -Utah ad\nmitted to the Union Serious,\ntrouble in Cuba Peary starts out\non his sixth expedition in search\nof the North Pole.\n'97 Great ebal strike in West Vir\nginiaNashville, Tenri.; Centen\nnial -Exposition opened Extra\nsession of Congress called and the\ntariff bill passed The Klondike\ngold fields discovered In Alaska.\n1833-1837\n1833 Passage of the Compromise\nTariff bill in the U. S. Removal of\nGovernment deposits from the U.\nS. Bank, by President Jackson\nDeath of Molly Pitcher.\n34 Organization of the Whig party\nin the U. S.\n'35 Exclusion of anti-slavery litera\nture from the U. S. mails Passage\nof the act against anti-slavery pe\ntitions called the \"Atherton Gag\"\nEntire public debt of the U. S.\nwas discharged and surplus divid\ned between the States.\n'36 Election of Martin Van Buren\nPresident of the U. S. Texan in\ndependence of Mexico declared\nand won at San Jacinto Inven\ntion of screw propeller by John\nEricsson.\n'37 Michigan admitted to the Union\nRemains of Washington re\nmoved to Mount Vernon Great\nFinancial Panic eight States went\nbankrupt; the Government could\nnot pay the interest on its bonds.\nfT T\nITT\nGOODS\n1898-1902\n1898 Greater New York begins its\nofficial existence The U. S. bat\ntleship Maine blown up in Havana\nHarbdr Spain declares war Ad\nmiral Dewey captures Manila\nProtocol of peace signed at Wash\nington.\n99 New York's reception to Ad\nmiral Dewey War in Philippines\nAssassination of Governor Goebel\nDiscovery of wireless telegraphy.\n1900 The Galveston flood The\n\"Boxer\" outbreak in China Re\nelection of President McKinley\nTheodore Roosevelt Vice-President.\n'Ol Death of ex-President Harrisons-President\nMcKinley assassi\nnated at Buffalo Mr. Roosevelt\nsucceeds to the Presidency.\nU2 The great coal strike Bill for\nthe purchase of the Panama Canal\npassed by congress Earthquake\nat Martineaque.\n1838-1842\n1838 Arrival of Great Western from\nEngland The Smithsonian Insti\ntution established Lieut. Charles\nWilkes's expedition to the South\nPole.\n'39 Envelopes for letter correspond\nence first used in this country.\n'40 Congress passed bill allowing\nTreasury to issue notes for $10,000\n000 Campaign of General Har\nrison, called the \"Hard Cider\"\ncampaign Anti-rent war in New\nYork State.\n'41 Reduction of tariff Inaugura\ntion of President Harrison; his\ndeath on April 4 due to exposure\nat the time of his inauguration\nVice-President Tyler became Presi\ndent. '42 End of Seminole War Extradi\ntion treaty enacted between Eng\nland and the U. S. Augustus\nPorter formulates the scheme of\nhydraulic canals.\n1858-1862\nI8S8 Minnesota admitted to the\nUnion First Atlantic cable com\npleted by Cyrus VV. FieldGold\ndiscovered at Pike's Peak.\n'59 Oregon admitted to the Union\nJohn Brown seizes Harper's\nFerry; was later captured and\nhung Credit Mobilier of America\norganized.\n'60 President Lincoln elected Se\ncession of South Carolina.\n'61 Southern Confederacy organized\nBombardment of Fort Sumter\nCapture of Harper's Ferry Battle\nof Bull Run President Lincoln\ncalls for militia Capture of Fed\neral Craft by Confederate steamer\nAlabama.\n62 Battle of Shiloh The Monitor\ndefeats the Merrimac Second\nbattle of Bull Run Battles of An\ntietam and Fredericksburg\n\"Greenbacks\" issued First over\nland railway.\n1863-1867\n1863 Emancipation proclamation is\nsued National banking sytem\ntablished BattleofLookoutMoun\ntain Draft riots in New York\nBattle of Gettysburg.\nt\n'64 Sheridan's ride Sherman's\nmarch to the sea. Lincoln re-elected.\n'65 Laying of the second American\ncable Adoption of the Thirteenth\nAmendment Evacuation of Rich\nmond Surrender of Lee Assassi'\nnation of Lincoln Death of Wilkes\nBooth Close of the Rebellion.\n66 Proclamation that Civil War is\nover Establishment of first post\nof the Grand Army of the Republic\nTennessee restored to the Union.\nr.\n67 Jefferson Davis was released\nfrom prison-Purchase of Alaska\nfrom Russia. Nebraska was ad\nmitted to the Union.\n1868-1872\n1868 The impeachment and acquit\ntal of Andrew Johnson Adoption\nof the Fourteenth Amendment\nGeneral Grant elected President of\nthe United States Cuban Rebel\nlion. 69 Completion of the Overland\nRailway Financial panic \"Black\nFriday,\" Sept, 24 The \"Tweed\nring\" Outcry against the influx\nof Chinese\n70 National census taken; popula\ntion of the United States 38,559,871\nDeath of General Lee and Ad\nmiral Farragut Commenced oper\nations on Brooklyn Bridge.\n'71 The Great Chicago fire Passage\nof the Force Bill All the States\nadmitted to representation in\nCongress.\n'72 The northwestern boundry line\nquestion settled President Grant\nwas re-elected Civil war in Arkan\nsas The Apache outrages Hor\nace Greeley died.\n1903-1907\n1903 First cable message a